{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85bf06e6-b7dd-4e2c-be7a-8ccd7b6a72ee","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Note: macOS disables core dumps by default, and SIP may prevent them entirely.\n\nSince `createdump` isn't bundled with NativeAOT apps, the `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is typically your best bet — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d99cac06-16f3-4771-878d-48675a0abfbf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":304,"requestId":"7645:214D4D:1A60240:1DEEAD6:69FE925E"},"id":"72da9af7-ff92-4777-9b69-4916d67684cf","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:48:23.717Z","parentId":"245e42a1-f666-4399-ab80-95c0f8f50515"}
